		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2009"></a><br><code>sle2009/paper03</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Study of an API Migration for Two XML APIs</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ThiagoTonelliBartolomei.html">Thiago Tonelli Bartolomei</a>, <a href="../profile/KrzysztofCzarnecki.html">Krzysztof Czarnecki</a>, <a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>, <a href="../profile/TijsvanderStorm.html">Tijs van der Storm</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_5">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_5</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagM">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> The paper studies migration between two XML APIs, treating APIs as the primary language-like artifacts.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> API migration is a form of software/language evolution and maintenance driven by change over time.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Migration typically requires systematic mapping/conversion between old and new API usages.
</li></ul></li></ul>
